  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Keeping the Tweed in Order" imageAlt="Scottish Terrier puppy having its wiry coat and beard combed" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Scottie coat is low-shedding but not no-work: brush 2 to 3 times a week, with particular attention to the beard, leg furnishings and skirt where tangles start, and a proper groom every 6 to 8 weeks. Show dogs are hand-stripped; pet Scotties here are clipped, which softens the coat over time and suits our climate and budgets perfectly well.</p>
      <p>The beard collects meals and investigations, so a quick daily comb-and-wipe keeps it presentable, and in our humidity, dry the undercarriage properly after wet-grass walks. All the starting tools are in your kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Scottie Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Scottish Terrier puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Scottie goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Scottie health points worth knowing, honestly: "Scottie cramp", a harmless, odd-looking gait hiccup under excitement that needs no treatment, just recognition; von Willebrand's disease, a clotting disorder in some lines, worth asking about before any surgery; and the one serious item, the breed carries a higher-than-average rate of bladder cancer in later life, which is why we tell every Scottie owner the same simple habit: take any blood in the urine seriously, at any age, and ask your vet about it early. Early detection changes outcomes.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Scottie's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Scottish Terrier puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Scottie conducts its inspection, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and unhurried acquaintance; the Scottie decides about people on its own schedule, and rushing it backfires.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks and the household is formally adopted. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; with an independent breed, early respectful structure is worth double. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

